t, in Vedic =\r\nphilosophy, there is no anatman. All that is is \natman (Self). Ocean is per=\r\nmanent and still, but ripples that arise in it are \ntransient and moving. B=\r\nut ripples are part of ocean only and you do not start \nlabeling ripples as=\r\n &quot;non-ocean&quot;. \n\n  \nAtman or Purusha or Shiva is the potential energy of thi=\r\ns cosmos, while Maya or \nPrakriti or Shakti is the kinetic energy of this c=\r\nosmos. Shiva and Shakti are \nseen as different entities by some people, but=\r\n rishis have declared their \noneness. Potential energy becomes kinetic ener=\r\ngy and vice versa. \n\n  \nAtman is the still ocean and Maya is the force (kin=\r\netic) that gives rise to \nmoving ripples on the surface. A ripple that exer=\r\nts itself to move in a \nparticular way keeps colliding with the force and k=\r\neeps moving hither and tither \nin a chaotic way for a very long time. A rip=\r\nple that does not exert itself and \nmoves smoothly as dictated by the force=\r\n will eventually grind to a halt and \ncease to exist as a ripple on the sur=\r\nface. It then becomes part of the still \nocean. If a ripple exerts itself t=\r\no become still, it may even take longer to \nbecome still. What prolongs a r=\r\nipple is not movement but resisting the direction \ngiven by the force and e=\r\nxerting to move in a particular way (or even exerting to \nbecome still). A =\r\nripple that surrenders to the force will ride the course and \ndie down fast=\r\ner. \n\n  \nContemplate the imagery I presented above regarding Atman and Maya=\r\n, \nignorant/egoistic action and detached action! It is very apt. \n\n  \n*    =\r\n    *        * \n  \nIn not-so-distant past, sannyasins remained in ashrams a=\r\nnd isolated themselves \nfrom society and did their sadhana. Swami Vivekanan=\r\nda started a new trend. \n\n  \nA sannyasin renounces expectation of things fr=\r\nom people stuck in transient \nmaterial world and does not depend on anyone.=\r\n But he may still *give* basic \nmaterial things to those hapless people stu=\r\nck in transient material world! For \nexample, Swami Vivekananda and his bro=\r\nther monks went to places struck by \nplague, floods, droughts, cyclones etc=\r\n and served people. They provided food, \nmedicines etc (instead of lecturin=\r\ng that body is a transient illusion and one \nshould stop worrying about its=\r\n welfare!) and also did construction work. They \nignored the welfare of the=\r\nir own bodies, put themselves at risk and overcame \nmaya personally. But th=\r\ney served those still stuck in maya without looking down \nupon them or thei=\r\nr needs or maya that trapped them! Those who wanted food got \nfood, those w=\r\nho wanted medicines got medicines and those who wanted books got \nbooks. Re=\r\nnunciation means you do not expect anything from anyone and accept \nwhateve=\r\nr comes to you naturally. It does not necessarily mean rejecting or \nignori=\r\nng others. Overcoming maya does not require belittling maya or belittling \n=\r\nthose still stuck in maya. \n\n  \nThe trend started by Swami Vivekananda was =\r\ncontinued by Swami Sivananda. For \nthat reason, it is a bit weird to see hi=\r\nm talking so ill of action! He was \nobviously trying to inspire a specific =\r\ngroup of people for a specific body of \nwork. These words are neither unive=\r\nrsal nor do they reflect his tremendous \nwisdom I have seen elsewhere! \n\n  =\r\n\n*        *        * \n  \nAll this intellectual discussion may be satisfying=\r\n to some, but the quote from \nSwami Brahmanananda in the other mail is very=\r\n apt: &quot;You have been only hearing \nof all these spiritual things. Now reali=\r\nse them. You have done enough study and \nreasoning. Now do some spiritual p=\r\nractice. First take up that aspect of God \nwhich appeals to you most. Follo=\r\nw your own path of Sadhana. When you realise God \nthrough it, you will feel=\r\n the joy of realising Him also in other aspects and \nthrough other paths.&quot; =\r\n\n\n  \nAccording to Ramakrishna, Swami Brahmananda was a gopala who accompani=\r\ned Lord \nKrishna in a previous life. His words are simple, pragmatic and po=\r\nwerful. \n\n  \nI want this forum to facilitate exchange of Vedic knowledge (a=\r\nnd I will also be \ncontributing, though in spurts). But I want more that th=\r\nis forum should inspire \npeople to do sadhana and find God. In the end, tha=\r\nt is what matters. \n\n  \nBest regards, \nNarasimha \n-------------------------=\r\n------------------------------------------ \n  Free Jyotish Software, Free J=\r\nyotish Lessons, Jyotish Writings, \n&quot;Do It Yourself&quot; ritual manuals for shor=\r\nt Homam and Pitri Tarpana: \n                  http://www.VedicAstrologer.or=\r\ng \n     Films that make a difference: http://SaraswatiFilms.org \n     Spiri=\r\ntuality: http://groups.yahoo.com/group/vedic-wisdom \n  Jyotish writings: ht=\r\ntp://groups.yahoo.com/group/JyotishWritings \n                     Twitter I=\r\nD: @homam108 \n-------------------------------------------------------------=\r\n------ \n  \nOn Mon, Jun 20, 2011 at 2:31 PM, Krishnendu wrote: \n\n    Some ma=\r\ny say: =C3=A2From. this it follows that it is not necessary for a knower \ne=\r\nven to serve his preceptor or to perform tapas.=C3=A2 Householders who are =\r\nafraid of \nbegging for bread and are afraid of ridicule argue like this thr=\r\nough their sharp \nintelligence. You cannot say that even begging for bread =\r\nis a binding rule on a \nsannyasin. That is not a desire and the sannyasin i=\r\ns virtually a mendicant \nwithout rules binding him. He is not liable to any=\r\n kind of command. Even one who \ndoes not know Brahman but who is desirous o=\r\nf emancipation should enter into the \norder of a sannyasin. The sruti says:=\r\n =C3=A2Let one live in the order of sannyasa \nwhich is a means to the knowl=\r\nedge of Brahman.=C3=A2 Brahmacharya may help one to \nattain knowledge but i=\r\nt is not th